description.plain:
“Honey” illustrates the fluidity of love and the comfort she feels with her lover, both spiritually and sexually.

The idea of honey, a free-flowing liquid that tempts people with its flavour and benefit, serves as a metaphor for the love and hard work needed to make a relationship taste as sweet as honey. Honey is hard to collect and takes a long time to create, just like Raveena’s ability to feel such a compelling connection.

body.plain:
“Honey” illustrates the fluidity of love and the comfort she feels with her lover, both spiritually and sexually.

The idea of honey, a free-flowing liquid that tempts people with its flavour and benefit, serves as a metaphor for the love and hard work needed to make a relationship taste as sweet as honey. Honey is hard to collect and takes a long time to create, just like Raveena’s ability to feel such a compelling connection.

annotations: My cup is fuller when you’re there

Raveena plays on the popular expression “Glass half full” to represent the joy and comfort that her partner brings her. With her lover around, Raveena dons her rose-colored glasses and views everything in an optimistic light.

This line plays off the infamous Mary Poppins track “A Spoonful of Sugar.”

https://youtu.be/k6o0WuaZOLo

Any difficult or frightening task can always be improved by accompanying it with a pleasant aspect; the mere presence of Raveena’s partner soothes her and lifts her spirits.

Doves are commonly associated with tranquility and love, and act as a symbol of peaceful messengers.



Raveena specifies seeing six doves while with her lover. The number six is known to represent two contrasting symbols: weakness and loving, protecting nature. In one sense, Raveena feels a weakness for her partner, always giving into them and needing them to help her grow. In another sense, the love that they share acts as a protecting and comforting nature to Raveena and her soul.

You’re milk and honey
 A drink I drink before bed, mm
 Don’t you feel lucky
 That we can end the day like that? Mm-mm

Raveena references a popular aphrodisiac here, first being used as far back as 500BC for its beneficial effects on sexual health.

It was said that Hippocrates, one of the most notable figures in the history of medicine, would prescribe milk and honey to induce love and ecstasy.

body.plain: “Petal” explores what it feels like to let go and come to peace with death. The final song on her first-full length album “Lucid,” filled with airy layered vocals, serves as a peaceful “death” to the album itself.

annotations:
When I feel like I’m down
 From checking my phone
 I will laugh when I cry
 ’Cause we all go alone

In keeping with the extrospective perception of reality, Raveena acknowledges the overwhelming control that technology and media have on people’s lives.

She touched on these lines with VICE, saying:

You can be mad about some stupid email but at the end of the day you should be enjoying life like my grandma says. We have such little time on this Earth, why waste it?

The preceding track is nearly two minutes of Raveena’s aforementioned grandmother blessing listeners with her wisdom and thoughts on fulfilling our lives. As Nani’s words flow into the beginning of “Petal,” Raveena’s ability to move forward from her trauma and focus on the good in life defies all odds, as we’re reminded that the most valuable moments of life exist outside of a phone and its chains that we’re bound to.
